article.description:
Kenny Thomas scored a career-high 31 points, and Steve Francis had 24 as the Houston Rockets beat Golden
State 116-104 Sunday night, snapping their four-game losing streak and extending the Warriors' skid to 10 games.
article.headline: Thomas has career night for Rockets
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- As low as the Houston Rockets have been lately, they still aren't low enough to lose to the Golden State Warriors.
Thomas

Kenny Thomas scored a career-high 31 points, and Steve Francis had 24 as the Rockets beat Golden State 116-104 Sunday night, snapping their four-game losing streak and extending the Warriors' skid to 10 games. Thomas scored seven straight points in the final minutes as Houston held on after blowing most of a 16-point lead in the second half. The Rockets finished the game on an 11-2 run, clinching a much-needed victory after losing on the first three stops of a five-game trip by an average of 20 points. It was the 13th straight victory over the Warriors for the Rockets, who are determined to salvage something from a dismal season that has included a 15-game losing streak and constant injury woes for Francis, their All-Star guard. Houston won't make the playoffs, but coach Rudy Tomjanovich believes his team already can start building for next year. "This was a big game for us to keep our spirits up," Tomjanovich said. "I kept telling our guys that when our lead was around six points, it was important that we got a stop on defense. We didn't want to get into a one-possession situation, because we've lost too many close games this year." Bob Sura had 19 points for Golden State, which dropped into a tie with Memphis for the worst record in the Western Conference at 17-52. Antawn Jamison added 17 points and seven rebounds as the Warriors lost their sixth straight home game. "This is like the way the season's been going," Jamison said. "We have an opportunity that can make or break us, and we found a way to break." Francis led Houston to a 77-61 advantage in the third quarter, but the Warriors gradually rallied. Golden State pulled within 105-102 on Sura's free throws with 4:11 left, but Thomas made a three-point play and four straight free throws on Houston's next three possessions. "The last few games, I don't think we competed like we should and like we can," Thomas said. "Steve got me a lot of shots in this one by penetrating and kicking it out to me. I just hit a bunch of them." Six players from each team scored in double figures in a wide-open, up-tempo game. Houston made 19 turnovers -- a season-high nine by Francis -- but Thomas and Francis shot their way past the woeful Warriors. Golden State, just 5-39 in 2002, is on its longest losing streak since dropping 13 straight to close last season. The Warriors also matched the Grizzlies' NBA-worst 11-24 home record. "It's been a chronic problem -- every time we get in a close game, we find a way to shoot ourselves in the foot," Warriors coach Brian Winters said. "Whatever it is, we need to get over it. We're playing some younger guys, and experience wins in this business. It's been proven through the years." In the first half, Francis broke out of his shooting slump with 19 points. He shot just 36 percent in his previous eight games, a drop-off he attributed to a nagging shoulder injury sustained March 8 in a loss to Golden State -- also the Warriors' last victory. "I felt good, even though my shoulder is still messed up," Francis said. "This is the first decent game I've had with my shoulder for a while. I got some lift on my shot." Adonal Foyle had 12 points, eight rebounds and five blocked shots in an effective performance for Golden State, while rookie Gilbert Arenas had three 3-pointers among his 16 points. Walt Williams scored just seven points for the Rockets, but on one strange possession, he picked up three personal fouls and a technical foul for arguing with Jamison. Game notes
Jason Collier had a season-high 10 points for Houston. ... Neither team shot a free throw until Jamison's three-point play with 1:50 left in the first quarter. ... Rockets rookie Eddie Griffin missed his third straight game with a sprained toe. He has returned to Houston to heal. The Rockets' road trip wraps up Tuesday at Utah.
